>The War on Drugs could be stopped. Think of it as a security problem.=20
>The threat is "drugs are available in the US at free-market prices".=20
>If there were a sucessful attack (ie, drugs became available at=20
>free-market prices) the cost would be in the trillions of dollars per=20
>year to the drug industry (ie, traffickers, law enforcement, military=20
>anti-drug enforcement, intelligence agencies, etc). To prevent this=20
>threat from happening, two things need to be done: one, drugs must be=20
>stopped at the border; and two, drugs must not be produced inside the=20
>US. A certain large amount of money is spent on these two security=20
>policies.=20
>=20
>Billions of packages move in and out of the US every year. Every=20
>single one of them could contain drugs. If something were done to=20
>radically increase the cost of hunting for drugs in these packages,=20
>the War would come to an end. Likewise, a huge amount of stuff is=20
